<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONTROVERSY OVER BART SIMPSON: 'UNDERACHIEVER AND PROUD OF IT' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a teacher in an alternative high school diploma program for high-risk young 
people (dropouts and potential dropouts), I think Bart is one of the best 
things that has come along. The main reasons are this: 
</P>
<P>
1. 
</P>
<P>
There is less graffiti writing and more Bart doodling! One constant part of 
working in programs like this is keeping the classroom graffiti free. 
</P>
<P>
2. All ethnic groups relate to Bart. It is important to have images that all 
students can relate to -- especially in terms of color, race and creed. Believe 
it or not, Bart being a cartoon character is more powerful than Bill Cosby in 
that whites, Latinos, Asians, Samoans -- all young males seem to relate to the 
character. 
</P>
<P>
3. We, the adults in their lives, need to have clues on the "culture" of being 
young -- especially since so many of us have forgotten it. 
</P>
<P>
High school students must dream, daydream, doodle, be understood, have 
something that connects them to each other over race lines and to us over age 
lines. Seeing students come to class in clean, brightly colored Bart T-shirts 
and doodling with Bart cartoons is wonderful! 
</P>
<P>
The following is the writing of one 16-year-old black male in my class (a rough 
draft -- please look at the content). This young man is a particular fan of 
Bart. 
</P>
<P>
MARY M. BRADLEY, 
</P>
<P>
Coordinator, Learning Center 
</P>
<P>
San Pedro Wilmington Skills Center 
</P>
