<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEST SANDWICHES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON, Neil Solomon is the author of Sick &amp; Tired of Being 
Sick &amp; Tired, Wynwood Press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: My children take peanut butter sandwiches to school every day. They 
enjoy them, I've been told that peanut butter is nutritious, and the sandwiches 
take very little time to prepare. 
</P>
<P>
But I've noticed that there's usually a little bit of oil at the top of the 
jar, and I'm becoming concerned that my children are getting too much 
cholesterol. Would you please let me know how much cholesterol there is in 
peanut butter, compared, for example, with a frankfurter? Which would be better 
for them to have? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: One frankfurter provides about 34 milligrams of cholesterol. Peanut 
butter is not an animal product, and therefore does not contain any 
cholesterol. On all counts, a peanut butter sandwich, particularly if prepared 
with whole wheat bread, would be much more nutritious than a frankfurter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
