<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 CAJUN, ZYDECO PROS KEEP MUSIC PURE, TRADITIONAL; 
</P>
<P>
FESTIVAL: PURISTS WILL PERFORM THE MUSIC OF THEIR LOUISIANA HOMELAND IN LONG 
BEACH THIS WEEKEND. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RANDY LEWIS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To Cajun and zydeco music veterans D.L. Menard and John Delafose, there's 
nothing wrong with younger performers who mix elements of traditional Louisiana 
music with rock, blues and modern-day country to reach a wider audience. 
</P>
<P>
But for themselves, the music of their homeland is like air itself: the purer 
the better. 
</P>
<P>
In Menard's case, that means that as a guitarist, even though he has the 
technical proficiency to toss off juicy jazz and blues licks, he mostly eschews 
the fancy stuff in favor of basic three-chord strumming behind his old-timey 
two-steps and waltzes. 
</P>
<P>
For Delafose, it means still singing the bulk of his zesty zydeco songs in the 
traditional Cajun French, instead of abandoning his native tongue to lure 
English-speaking audiences. 
</P>
<P>
And what that means to those who catch Menard and Delafose this weekend, at the 
fourth annual Southern California Cajun and Zydeco Festival in Long Beach, is 
that they'll be hearing rural Louisiana music pretty much the way it has 
sounded for decades throughout Cajun country. (In addition to Saturday and 
Sunday performances by Menard's Louisiana Aces and Delafose's family-dominated 
Eunice Playboys, this year's lineup includes two other Louisiana acts -- 
relative newcomer Nathan (Williams) &amp; the Zydeco Cha-Chas and accordionist 
Bruce Daigrepont's Cajun Band -- plus three California-based groups. There also 
will be dance workshops and Cajun and Creole cooking available at booths set up 
by local restaurateurs.) 
</P>
<P>
Ask Menard and he'll be at the front of the line defending such crossover acts 
as Beausoleil, Zachary Richard and Wayne Toups, who have gained ground in rock 
circles. 
</P>
<P>
"You play music the way you feel it," Menard, 58, said by phone last week from 
his one-man chair factory in Erath, La., where he turns out custom wood 
straight-backs and rockers when he isn't on tour. Road trips have taken him 
around the United States several times as well as to Europe, Central and South 
America and the Far East. 
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't bother me if Wayne Toups jumps up and down on stage and does a 
split -- I'm all for it, if that's the way he likes it. I feel like doing it 
real straight -- that's the way I'm comfortable with it and that's the way I'll 
keep on doing it." 
</P>
<P>
Much in Menard's outlook can be traced back to a chance 10-minute chat with his 
idol Hank Williams nearly 40 years ago, though he still talks about it as if it 
happened last week. 
</P>
<P>
"Hank Williams told me this one time -- he said: 'All music is good if it is 
your music,' " said Menard, who has been dubbed the "Cajun Hank Williams" for 
plaintive vocals that sound, when he sings in English, eerily like those of the 
country-music giant. 
</P>
<P>
It's a moniker he accepts politely, but with a blush. "It don't bother me. If 
people see me that way, I'm grateful," he said in the distinctly syncopated 
Cajun accent. "But there was only one Hank Williams and nobody is gonna touch 
his shoes." 
</P>
<P>
Menard's Louisiana Aces band currently includes his longtime, champion 
fiddle-playing cohort Ken Smith and accordionist Eddie LeJeune, the son of 
Cajun music great Iry LeJeune. In a warm-up for this weekend's festival, Menard 
and his group will play a Cajun dance Friday at the War Memorial Hall in South 
Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
John Delafose is often mentioned along with Boozoo Chavis, Rockin' Dopsie and 
Buckwheat Zydeco's Stanley (Buckwheat) Dural as a leading contender for the 
"King of Zydeco" crown left in 1987 by the death of Clifton Chenier. 
</P>
<P>
But Delafose isn't particularly worried about when, or if, that crown will be 
passed. Chenier is pretty much credited with inventing zydeco, the rollicking, 
rhythm-and-blues infused strain of Cajun music, and Delafose, 51, notes that 
"in Clifton's time, it was only Clifton for a while. But there are so many 
(zydeco) bands around now, it's hard to have a single person as the people's 
choice." 
</P>
<P>
"Now," the accordionist added with a chuckle, over the phone from his home in 
Eunice, La., about 40 miles northwest of Lafayette, "Rockin' Dopsie has got 
himself a crown and says he's the king. But I think that should be appointed by 
the people. Anyway, it's all right if I'm not the king -- as long as I get the 
most gigs." 
</P>
<P>
If Delafose has a concern, it's that too many bands may stray from the musical 
source point. But his family is doing its part: Son Geno, who plays drums for 
the Eunice Playboys, also plays accordion and speaks Cajun French, "so he's 
gonna have a good zydeco band of his own one day." Another of Delafose's sons, 
Tony, is the Playboys' bass player. 
</P>
<P>
Some advocates hoped that "The Big Easy" film in 1987, with its Cajun and 
zydeco-rich soundtrack, would catapult Louisiana music to the national 
forefront the way "Urban Cowboy" did for country music in the early '80s. 
Menard and Delafose don't fret much that it didn't work out that way. 
</P>
<P>
"In some ways maybe people were disappointed, but it's still growing," said 
Delafose, who also plays tonight at Patout's Cajun restaurant in Westwood and 
Friday at Verbum Dei High School in Compton, which not coincidentally was 
Clifton Chenier's favorite Southland concert stop. 
</P>
<P>
"People come to (the annual New Orleans Jazz &amp; Heritage) festival from all 
different areas," Delafose said. "Now there's other (Cajun-zydeco) festivals in 
California, Texas, San Francisco, Rhode Island. People will go to a festival 
and like it, then go home and spread it out." 
</P>
<P>
In that respect, both men line up squarely in the corner of Southland 
Cajun-Zydeco Festival organizer Franklin Zawacki, who organizes the Southern 
California festival out of his brother's house in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
"I prefer the way it's going now," said Zawacki, a music lover who's more 
likely to be found in front of the bandstand dancing Cajun style than 
sequestered backstage in an office tallying gate receipts. "I'd rather have 
people come to the music, like it and then love it, rather than wear it in a 
hip fashion for a while and then lose interest next season." 
</P>
<P>
 The fourth annual Southern California Cajun &amp; Zydeco Festival takes place 
Saturday and Sunday from noon to 7 p.m. at the Rainbow Lagoon, Long Beach 
Boulevard and Ocean Avenue, Long Beach. Tickets: $15 general; $12 students and 
seniors; free for children under 12. Information: (213) 867-2215 or (714) 
638-1466. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
