THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
ENGLAND TO HOST '93 RYDER CUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WENTWORTH, England 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The European Ryder Cup Committee spurned a strong bid by Spain and voted today 
to stage the 1993 Ryder Cup golf match against the United States at The Belfry 
in central England for the third time. 
</P>
<P>
Spain will stage the event the next time it is held in Europe in 1997 "subject 
to certain guarantees and contractual arrangements being forthcoming," the 
committee said. 
</P>
<P>
The decision boiled down to a straight fight between The Belfry, the choice of 
the European Professional Golfers Assn., and the Club de Campo in Madrid, 
favored by the PGA European Tour. 
</P>
<P>
The issue was decided on a vote cast by Lord Derby, chairman of the Ryder Cup 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
The Belfry, at Sutton Coldfield in the English Midlands, staged the event for 
the first time in 1985, when Europe wrested the trophy from the United States. 
Europe, which won for the second straight time in 1987 in the United States, 
retained the cup after last year's tie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
